```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>

using namespace std;

void solvePoint1(const vector<int>& balls, ofstream& outFile) {
    int n = balls.size();
    int sequenceCount = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ) {
        int j = i;
        while (j < n && balls[j] == balls[i]) {
            ++j;
        }
        ++sequenceCount;
        i = j;
    }
    outFile << sequenceCount << endl;
}

void solvePoint2(vector<int> balls, ofstream& outFile) {
    int n = balls.size();
    while (true) {
        int maxLen = 0, maxStart = -1;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; ) {
            int j = i;
            while (j < n && balls[j] == balls[i]) {
                ++j;
            }
            int len = j - i;
            if (len >= 3 && len > maxLen) {
                maxLen = len;
                maxStart = i;
            }
            i = j;
        }
        if (maxStart == -1) break;
        balls.erase(balls.begin() + maxStart, balls.begin() + maxStart + maxLen);
        n -= maxLen;
    }
    outFile << n << endl;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        outFile << balls[i] << endl;
    }
}

int main() {
    ifstream inFile("arc.in");
    ofstream outFile("arc.out");

    int V, n;
    inFile >> V >> n;
    vector<int> balls(n);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        inFile >> balls[i];
    }

    if (V == 1) {
        solvePoint1(balls, outFile);
    } else if (V == 2) {
        solvePoint2(balls, outFile);
    }

    inFile.close();
    outFile.close();
    return 0;
}
```

### Explanation:

1. **Reading Input**:
   - The input is read from `arc.in` using `ifstream`.
   - The first value `V` determines which part of the problem to solve.
   - The second value `n` is the number of balls.
   - The next `n` values are the colors of the balls, stored in a vector `balls`.

2. **Solving Point 1**:
   - The function `solvePoint1` counts the number of sequences in the initial list of balls.
   - It iterates through the list and counts contiguous segments of the same color.

3. **Solving Point 2**:
   - The function `solvePoint2` simulates the game.
   - It repeatedly finds the longest sequence of at least 3 balls, removes it, and checks for new sequences formed by the removal.
   - The process continues until no more sequences of length 3 or more can be removed.
   - The remaining balls are then written to `arc.out`.

4. **Writing Output**:
   - The results are written to `arc.out` using `ofstream`.

### Compilation and Execution:

To compile and run this code:
```sh
g++ -o arc_solution arc_solution.cpp
./arc_solution
```

Make sure `arc.in` is in the same directory as the executable. The output will be written to `arc.out`.
